<h2><a name="readings">Syllabus and Readings</a></h2>
<p>The following list summarizes the topics that will be covered in this
course. Also included are the required and optional readings for each
topic. <span style="font-weight: bold;">J&amp;M </span>refers to the
book "Speech and Language Processing" by Jurafsky and Martin; <span
 style="font-weight: bold;">WC&amp;O</span> refers to "Programming Perl
3rd Edition" by Wall, McLaughlin and Orwant; <span
 style="font-weight: bold;">Sipser </span>refers to "Introduction to
the Theory of Computation" by Michael Sipser (see below for detailed
information on each of these books). Apart from the required readings,
the optional or review readings are provided for those who are having
difficulty understanding the material. </p>
      <ol>
        <li>Introduction to Linguistics and Formal language theory</li>
        <ul>
          <li><a href="intro.pdf">Notes #1</a>
          <li>Chp 1 and 2 (J&amp;M)</li>
          <li><span style="font-style: italic;">Review:</span> Chp 0
and 1
(Sipser)</li>
          <li>Links: <a
 href="http://www.cstr.ed.ac.uk/projects/festival/">Text
to Speech</a>, <a href="http://www.naturalvoices.att.com/">Speech
Animation</a>, <a href="http://www1.cs.columbia.edu/nlp/newsblaster/">Summarization</a></li>
          <li>Links: <a
 href="http://www.speech.cs.cmu.edu/Communicator/">Dialog
Systems</a>, <a href="http://www.ionaut.com/">Question Answering</a>, <a
 href="http://www.semanticlight.com/">NLP &amp; Graphics</a></li>
        </ul>
        <li>Finite-state methods: automata and transducers
(applications to orthography, morphology, phonology)<br>
        </li>
        <ul>
          <li><a href="fsmapply.pdf">Notes #2</a>
          <li>Chp 1 and 2 (J&amp;M)</li>
          <li>Chp 3 (J&amp;M)</li>
          <li>Extra slides from Richard Sproat's CL course: <br>
          </li>
          <ul>
            <li><a href="sproat-slides06.pdf">Introduction to
computational phonology</a>, <br>
            </li>
            <li><a href="sproat-slides07.pdf">Compiling
context-dependent rewrite rules
into finite-state transducers</a><br>
            </li>
          </ul>
          <li>Links: An example NLP application using finite-state
transducers: <a href="http://acl.ldc.upenn.edu/J/J98/J98-4003.pdf">Machine
Transliteration</a>. Kevin Knight and Jonathan Graehl. Computational
Linguistics, Volume 24, Number 4, December 1998. <span
 style="font-style: italic;">(the pronunciation mapping for your homework
was taken from this paper)</span><br>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <li>Finite-state methods: edit distance (shortest path in a
transducer, spelling
correction, evaluation metrics)</li>
        <ul>
          <li>Chp 5 sections 5.1-5.6 (J&amp;M)</li>
          <li>Links: <a href="http://odur.let.rug.nl/%7Ekleiweg/lev/">Levenshtein
Demo</a><br>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <li>Probability models and language: n-grams<br>
        </li>
        <ul>
          <li>Reading: Sections 1-14 from <a href="mt-wkbk.pdf">Kevin
Knight's statistical MT workbook</a></li>
          <li>Reading: Sections 1-2.7 (p.15) &amp; Section 5.1 from <i></i><a
 href="../CMPT-413-Spring-2003/chen-goodman-tr-10-98.pdf"><i>Empirical
Study of Smoothing</i> by Chen and Goodman</a></li>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <ul>
          <li>Chp 6 sections 6.1-6.2 and 6.7 (J&amp;M).&nbsp;<span
 style="font-style: italic;"></span></li>
          <li><span style="font-style: italic;"><span
 style="font-weight: bold;">Warning:</span> it is essential to read the
errata pages for this chapter and do </span><span
 style="font-weight: bold; font-style: italic;">not</span><span
 style="font-style: italic;"> read sections 6.3-6.6 from
J&amp;M</span></li>
        </ul>
        <li>Hidden markov models (sequence learning)<br>
        </li>
        <ul>
          <li>Chp 5 section 5.9; sections 7.1-7.3 and Appendix D
(J&amp;M)</li>
          </li>
          <li>Viterbi spreadsheet (Excel or Openoffice): <a
 href="viterbi.xls">viterbi.xls</a></li>
          <li>Forward-backward spreadsheet (Excel or Openoffice): <a
 href="hmm.xls">hmm.xls</a></li>
        </ul>
        <li>Some applications of sequence learning (automatic speech
recognition, part of speech tagging, name-finding,
word segmentation)<br>
        </li>
        <ul>
          </li>
          </li>
          <li>Chp 8 sections 8.1-8.5 (J&amp;M)</li>
        </ul>
        <li>Context-free grammars and parsing algorithms (natural
language syntax)<br>
        </li>
        <ul>
          <li>Parsing demos using the Python <a
